the most elegant women
the most sophisticated
demure
desirable
can wear pain like a diamond necklace
like a fine trousseau
like a subtle, elegant broach
that wearing it that way
is mature
beautiful
the high road
well, i am here to tell you
we're not wearing shit
we are beautiful
naked
and if that scares you
good
so, it's not your fault for causing the pain?
it's our fault for wearing it wrong?
tell you what
you wear it

text:
‚Äúone year after metoo‚Äù
that‚Äôs what they say, and they ask ‚Äúwhere are we now?‚Äù
that‚Äôs the question i ask. 
where are we now?
a year ago, metoo was basically viewed as a revolution. sure, is women made the world stop for just a moment. we became a force.
but then the backlash came, where women were spoken of as attention seeking, just ‚Äúafter his money‚Äù... at the same time, here in sweden, women were asking something for men, for them to tell how they were perpetrators. after all, we all know a victim, but never a perpetrator, right? suddenly the perpetrators got faces and names. 
they were called brave.
whereas women who came forward about their rapes were considered liars. they still are.
dr ford is a perfect example of that.

something we all need to think about is this:
what do women gain from lying about being raped? they don‚Äôt get fame nor money. they get harassed.
what do perpetrators gain from lying about them actually committing the crime? 
what‚Äôs more likely?
that a woman lies about being a victim of rape or that a man lies about not have raped her?
#metoo #istandwithher #istandwithford #feminism

text:
thursday night tea with anthony is back with another amazing episode this thursday at 6pm.

do you watch pose fx? ever wondered what it would be like to go to an actual ball? the legendary duante balenciaga with be here to discuss the on the run ball: where in the world? it's taking place here in dc.

in the wake of the #metoo movement, we want to shed light on sexual abuse. damika kelly at love queen meko has written a phenomenal book. we'll discuss that and a new film.

our live performers, sol & muse, will be setting the stage ablaze with their melodic intertwining voices.

tune in this thursday evening at 6pm at www.listenvisionlive.com, fb live, or just stop by the studio. either way, come get this tea!

text:
back in april, a wonderful woman named vanessa filley reached out to me about taking part in a photo project of hers that involved #metoo. her description was: ‚Äúthe project encompasses women young and old from varied backgrounds and aims to create a bridge from women in the past to women speaking out today, to give voice to all the untold stories throughout history‚Äù. the photo project is making its way through the us, being shown in galleries and exhibits from california to new york, to the great midwest that falls in-between.

now more than ever, it is so important to stand strong and resist those that continue to try and push us back down. my photo is only one of many, and we stand for those throughout time that had/have stories to tell. we speak for them, we support them, and we say, #metoo.

text: anita hill// thank you.  27 years ago... you lead this fight we are still embroiled in... you weren‚Äôt protected enough then but you fought with dignity anyway.  you answered the call placed before you.  we‚Äî i‚Äôm talking #blackwomen‚Äî are often the #pioneers for everything.  we have to be. the intersections of our gender and race renders us often overlooked, undervalued and left alone to speak for ourselves and our children.  i always say if we can solve the issues that plague black women, this country would truly be the best place on earth.  it astonishes me how #brave #strong and #consistent we are generation after generation.  often history will tell you it was only the black men and white women who lead movements of humanity and equality. but we‚Äôve been here, always have been.  you were there 27 years ago... fighting for us!  you sitting there at #clarencethomas confirmation hearings, you had everything to lose... but you made a crack that day, that will eventually break the dam... thank you for being patient with the rest of us to speak up and say #metoo! (another pioneering black woman @taranajaneen who is leading us in this moment) #inthelandof #pioneeringpapillion #pioneeringpatriot

text:
the scope of the metoo movement is large, and that has been proven no better than through its expansion into china, arguably one of the most oppressed countries in the world. any sexual related topic is largely taboo to speak about in chinese society, and this matched with a government that has no qualms about censoring its citizens has lead to any sexual abuse or harassment victims almost never coming forward (kuo). this mentality is changing thanks to the #metoo movement and its worldwide influence. a handful of accusations have been made against prominent figures in chinese society including three journalists, two badminton coaches, and a well known television host (kuo). the government has attempted to stop the influence of metoo, censoring chinese social media platforms by blocking any mention of the movement (kao). one of the accusers at the forefront of this movement asked to remain anonymous in her interview with ‚Äúthe guardian‚Äù, however still weighing in on the obstacles women face saying, ‚Äúeven the strictest censorship cannot stop someone from standing up and speaking out.‚Äù it seems the #metoo movement may, against all odds, offer chinese women the courage to speak out among others all over the world. (article credit: kuo, lily. ‚Äú#metoo in china: movement gathers pace amid wave of accusations.‚Äù the guardian, guardian news and media, 31 july 2018, www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jul/31/metoo-in-china-movement-gathers-pace-amid-wave-of-accusations.)
@sarablissjones @sumoske @sampsonuriah

text: you don‚Äôt think that an all inclusive holiday to the dominican republic would give you such a deep reflective opportunity, but it really has. i think it‚Äôs all the time i‚Äôve had to do nothing. i‚Äôve also been dreaming really vividly and they‚Äôre the kind of dreams that stick with you. a lot of dreams to do with the #metoo movement and my own experiences...just yesterday i had an experience, i was at the pool, just after this picture, a drunk guy stumbled over, he fell slightly and i caught his eye so i smiled, he lured at me, i stopped smiling, he called me a bitch, his friend then moved him away. nothing really happened in those moments but i felt uncomfortable enough to move away, it made me cross. i‚Äôve been thinking a lot about how i think about myself and how i can change my thoughts to make my relationship with myself better. i‚Äôve been thinking about body image, health, my physical pain and the experiences i‚Äôve had over the past year which have been hard. i‚Äôve also been thinking about the strength that i‚Äôve had to culminate throughout my life, which hasn‚Äôt always been easy. i guess i just wanted to post this because yes whilst im having an incredible time here and i feel hugely lucky to be able to have experiences like this, there‚Äôs also more to the smiley pictures you see on the beach... #brokenandstrong #reflection #thoughts

text:
it's as if we don't have to count our words anymore

instead of whispering don't go, 
you wrote him a letter
about the vacations you wished 
you could take with him

instead of telling him you love him
you told him the story 
about the times you ran back home
from school because men followed
you across the street and your friend
said, if we ran fast we might not end
up dead

the story didn't have anything
to do with his kisses that night,
but you just wanted him to know
if you shrunk from his touch
if you closed your eyes

it wasn't his fault
it wasn't his fault
.
.
/blame/

text:
‚Äúchrista,‚Äù edwina sandys, cathedral of st. john the divine

i took these photos back in the spring. i find this so very powerful and thought-provoking.
*
the only images i made then were these straight-on shots, perhaps because the question that grabbed me at the time was, what if? ‚Ä¶ what if you walked into church and this is what you saw? *
i‚Äôm still answering that for myself, and pondering follow-up questions: ‚Ä¶ about what it means to think of god as one of *us* ‚Ä¶ about lifting up the suffering of women as meaningful and redemptive ‚Ä¶ and about what it would mean to see ourselves and each other as ‚Äúfully represented in society, especially in its most powerful and iconic institutions,‚Äù as it says on the cathedral website ‚Ä¶ *
i‚Äôm still intending to find time to go back and contemplate this (with my heart and with my camera, of course) from other perspectives, but christa has been very much in my thoughts and prayers in this time.

#christa #stjohnthedivine #metoo #artthatspeaksvolumes

text:
john died 4 years ago today. 18 days before he turned 33. i turned 33 yesterday. it's odd to be older than my big brother. 
he was complex: intelligent, handsome, charismatic, emotionally abusive, violent, artistically inclined. my feelings around my brother are just as varied as he was a person. 
i've been ruminating over what it means to be older than him. i find myself motivated to work on myself. one big thing (a flaw shared with john) and a slew of little things. as of today, we have 90 days until the new year. i've seen lives change and miracles happen in 90 days. so, in dedicating myself to this list of life stuff that i want to work on. 
john, you motivate me to be a better person, to acknowledge my privledge, and to believe women when they say #metoo. i pray daily that you finally found the internal peace you deeply desired. i miss and love you. #suicideawareness

text:
listening for truth from the sacred rebels oracle by @alana_fairchild 
i drew this card for friend and later realized how perfect it is for our troubled times in america. #speakyourtruth "this oracle comes with a message of truth for you. you are hearing something that is not being said and what you are hearing is truthful. you may feel as though you are the only one that is really ready to hear or see it! perhaps you have been working in a situation or loving in a relationship, where truth is consistently denied.

we live in a world where truth is frequently avoided out of fear of what it might reveal. at the basis of such actions consciously or not is a deep sense of unhealed, toxic shame. if you or someone else, is fearful that the truth will expose rather than free and heal, then some personal healing is required. it is time for letting go of old wounds in favour of a greater sense of self-love and acceptance." <3

text:
the only way to lift the unbearably heavy weight of your secrets is to tell your truth.....hearts and souls are only temporary storage units, eventually the weight of what you carry needs to be released.  like purging the spaces around us, we also need to purge the spaces inside us.
those who don't believe you are not your problem......it's the fear of facing that disbelief that causes us to stay silent and like paul simon says, " silence like a cancer grows ".
you'll know when the time is right, it's when your inner dialogue becomes louder than the fear.
truth is a persistent s.o.b. 
and i am eternally grateful for that because it has many enemies ready to strike it down with arrows of doubt....stand tall because what you'll realize as those arrows are thrown in your direction is that they're hollow.
let them bounce off you and lay crumpled at your feet and look beyond them because behind their empty line of defence your army stands waiting.
truth doesn't need a strategy.
.

text:
‚Äúthe timing is just suspicious‚Äù
‚Äúwhy did you wait so long to come forward?‚Äù
‚Äúdid you tell anyone when it happened?‚Äù y‚Äôall.
abusers do not just ‚Äòlet it go‚Äô after the fact. they threaten you, your family, your reputation, your career, your lifestyle. they instill fear into their victims minds. survivors of abuse do not instantly feel safe and brave after the fact. we‚Äôre still scared. we‚Äôre still timid and trying to forget it or move past it.  many times, we don‚Äôt want to talk about our abuse. at all. i have many friends who only told their story and their truths for one of two reasons:
‚Ä¢ to save somebody else, (say , the victim after you who may have received escalated abuse at the hands of your abuser
or ‚Ä¢ because it was so severe cops were involved and you had no choice but to face the truth. 
i use my voice. i use it loud and hard, and not just for myself, but for my abuser‚Äôs victim after me, and for survivors still too afraid to share their story themselves. but i still have a depth to my story that i don‚Äôt share. because it‚Äôs still raw and scary and embarrassing, and i‚Äôm not ready to be that brave yet.

to  a n y o n e  who has shared their story, you are brave.

i will not question your timing of sharing your story.
i will not ask how many people you told when it happened.
i will not silence you.

share your story.  use your voice.
you never know who will be inspired and find their strength from you. üì∑: @raelynramey #wmnuprising

i had a deep, at times humorous, albeit real-talk interview with sunny megatron of american sex podcast last week and it's live: check out our conversation about all the sexual-socio-political important things and how we take good care of ourselves in the midst of it all. i always love talking to this woman--realness, rawness, sex and gender and all the things.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
after the week our country has had, this conversation is perfectly timed. sunny and amy jo discuss the impact of age of #metoo has had on various members of society‚Äìwomen, survivors, allies, non-binary folks, men, people of color, etc‚Äìand how our roles in it all intertwine. our discussion zeros in on how these factors affect women‚Äôs sexuality: why so many have difficulty focusing on pleasure and embracing desire, the struggle of getting sexual and emotional needs met, healing from trauma, feeling sexually ‚Äòbroken‚Äô, learning to be fully present in your body, and more. amy jo gives us a peek at the magic that goes on during private empowerment retreats plus gives tips for partners of those negatively affected by the kavanaugh hearings. sunny also announces some nifty new podcast swag on its way to patreon members.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

text:
üíêpasan los a√±os y lo √∫nico que valoramos es la experiencia de las cosas que se hicieron mal y las que se hicieron bien, esta foto me recuerda lo lindo de los 20‚Äôs la juventud, las ganas de explorar, las ganas de encasillar y sobresalir , las ganas de comerme el mundo !  pero en el fondo hab√≠a mucha inseguridad, manipulaci√≥n y tristeza, no era conforme ni con mi cuerpo, ni con mi vida, ten√≠a una relaci√≥n amorosa t√≥xica con un hombre manipulador y golpeador. que cada vez que se ‚Äúenrumbaba‚Äù con todos ‚Äúlos juguetes‚Äù la que tem√≠a era yo ! la que sufr√≠a las consecuencias era yo ! pero yo cre√≠a que lo amaba y no pod√≠a merecer mejor persona que el , al final siempre ven√≠a me ped√≠a disculpas, me llevaba a alg√∫n restaurante lujoso o club de moda en bogot√° y con eso se arreglaba la cosa. as√≠ poco a poco fui perdiendo mi personalidad y mi criterio y cr√©anme ha sido muy dif√≠cil recuperarla pas√≥ a paso primero matando todo tipo de contacto con el pasado , la persona en cuesti√≥n , las personas de mal ambiente,los lugares no tan buenos. hay que aprender a alejarnos de todo lo que nos hace da√±o y recoger pedazo por pedazo de lo que alguna vez fuimos y de lo que queremos ser y armarnos nuevamente . detr√°s de la belleza y la perfecci√≥n en esta foto, hab√≠an l√°grimas, soledad y falta de amor propio. no juzguemos a las mujeres por aguantar y callar, entre mujeres solo nos queda unirnos y apoyarnos! esto no es una moda, son cosas que pasan m√°s de lo que pensamos y en todos los estratos sociales. explotar y decir por lo que hemos pasado nos ayuda a no sentirnos como v√≠ctimas, (aunque v√≠ctimas ya somos) si no personas capaces de afrontar su realidad y sus problemas con la frente en alto y decir #yotambien y #yanotengomiedo ! #anorexiarecovery  photo by :  @morantesphoto .

text:
this picture symbolizes a great opportunity to reflect...
yes, it‚Äôs a leather jacket...
yes, there was a cut in the sleeve...
yes, it was bonded or mended back together...
yes, tacky glue was used...
yes, silk fabric was used on the underside to strengthen the adhesion...
yes, there is a shiny vs duller contrast after the repair...
yes, you can see the mend...
yes, it‚Äôs been altered forever...
yes, it‚Äôs no longer perfectly intact...
but *isn‚Äôt that the point‚ò∫Ô∏èüßêü§®...
i had an epiphany about wounds...
they create blemishes and alterations to what was original...
they draw attention to what was hurt or injured... but the operating word is *was*...
i have suffered miseries at the hands of many... some so unconscionable that i could justify quitting ... and at times i almost succeeded ... but ...
i am here now, looking at the scars and feeling a remnant pang of pain and i say, ‚Äúthank god, i‚Äôm alive... i can feel, i can breathe, i am freer than i have ever been in my entire life... i survived, i am thriving, i am loved, i love harder now because i know it‚Äôs what‚Äôs missing from the lives of many and somehow i have the capacity to give... it comes from an infinite source...it comes from the one who restores and heals and created me/us... i call him abba... i call him comforter...i call him my kinsmen redeemer...i call him father... i know him intimately...he knows me best...he knew me before i became ...‚Äù!!!! he is the bearer of hurt ...he is the giver of life...he is the healer of all wounds....
i marvel, looking at how i have been changed...i marvel at how i used to live life like an ostrich and now i live life like an eagle ü¶Ö and a dove....

text:
i'll never forget the last week - so i ask myself what i‚Äôve learned from all the turmoil and drama. ‚Ä¢
brothers, our sisters are weeping. they despair over the injustice of assault endured by the hands of men around us. if you do not see that - then you are either safe from sexual assault or it is being oppressed into silence around you.
‚Ä¢
before this week i did not know that 1 in every 6 women in america experiences an attempted or completed rape. i did not know that 95-97% of survivors who report a sexual assault are telling the truth. my lack of awareness is a product of my privilege as a white man in modern american culture. i am largely safe from that burden, so i was less attuned to its ubiquity in the lives of the women around me. until i listened to their stories.
‚Ä¢
listen to survivors‚Äô stories. believe them. they are telling the truth and the truth is shameful. modern men are failing our women. toxic masculinity is undermining our society and weakening the bonds that secure us all. worse, many of the men currently in charge of our government are either full of it themselves, or they‚Äôve been willing to look the other way. you cannot legislate to prevent sexual assault if you are either blind to it or a perpetrator of it.
‚Ä¢
the recent @vice documentary ‚Äúconsent‚Äù takes this necessary conversation to the edge. it pushes us all to revisit sexual encounters with a fresh perspective and ask ourselves challenging questions. it provokes exactly what we need a lot more of: conversation.
‚Ä¢
so to the men around me, brothers, i ask you to think about this deeply. do not shy away from this conversation. do not stay disengaged. if you are neutral in situations of injustice, you have chosen the side of the oppressor.

text: feeling so meh today! hate when i make plans and can't keep them or work myself up for something & then things go wrong. it seems to upset me so much and i just can't control my emotions or response! trying to push forward and make positive changes but finding it so hard. doesn't help that people i considered true friends, family even,  are slating me and don't seem to understand or accept me. i feel like people don't want to hear the truth and just tell you 'be strong' 'get over it' or 'get back to work!' well i am strong, i have been through more than i can bare to remember and i'm still here! i am getting through past trauma, recent trauma,  grief and current mental health & psychiatric issues at my own pace. recovery i am working just now,  in myself! i am the most important thing in my life for the first time ever and i am finally learning how important that is to accept. recovery is different for everyone and no-one has the right to force you to move faster than you are ready. that just pushes things back under the surface and they are never resolved. they fester away and can build up to a relapse and or in my case full mental break down! so please don't judge anyone, you don't know their story or what they have to go through just to survive each day! #peace #mentalsonthemove #dontjudge #recovery #atyourownpace #survivor #strong #innerstrength #iamimportant #metoo #haters #bitches #feelingdown #depression #mentalhealthwarrior #mentalhealthblog #blog #blogcomingsoon #adhd #trying #positive #changes #breakdown #relapse #l4l #lc #lfl #follow #pleaseshare

text: i do not believe this is a scary time for men in america. this is a wake up call and a chance for us to empower the boys and girls in our lives. it is my responsibility to teach my son about consent. that his body is his own and the bodies of others belong to them. to say that your son needs a body cam is to shirk our responsibility as teachers and to stop the communication we should be empowering our children to have with each other about their wants, needs, desires, and limits. ‚Äúboys will be boys‚Äù is not a phrase my son will hear. we take responsibility for our actions, and educate a better way when mistakes are made. i respect my son enough to know that he can learn how to treat others appropriately and i will expect him to lead others, who were not taught like he will be, by example.  #metoo #boymom #raisingboys #boyswillbegoodhumans #thefuture #respectwomen #respectyourself #feministmom #momgoals #stopkavanaugh #ibelieveher

text:
it's been a few weeks now that i started to really change my mentality and perspective on life. through taking the time to invest in myself and doing what i love (photography, youtube and writing) i‚Äôve found a new light in my life. i have also been sharing my depression, sexual assault and self-doubt stories with you all here and on my blog, and the amount of support i've received is even more uplifting. i constantly remind myself that no matter what the difficult circumstance may be, i have to acknowledge the good in the bad situations. allowing myself to trust my struggle and accept the fact that my overwhelming debt and foolish mistakes don't define me. they are just lessons i must learn to be better. every day, you can be better, and that's what i strive for. a better mind, attitude, and most importantly heart. remember to trust your struggle because 6 months to a year from now those things worrying you will no longer be relevant, so take action and be better one step at a time. üíñüôèüèΩüå∏.

text:
dear christine blasey ford,

thank you for speaking your truth and, in effect, giving me the courage to speak mine. #metoo 
it pains me to admit that it would take me a minute to count the number of men i‚Äôve given myself to mentally and physically. it hurts even more to know there are several i have forgotten entirely. it hurts the most that after those experiences i‚Äôve accepted unspeakable sexual and mental abuse because deep down i don‚Äôt believe i‚Äôm pure enough to be considered a victim, even in my own mind. 
now when i simply go on a date, kiss, or even talk to a guy it feels dirty. i feel dirty. because i‚Äôm letting them in. i‚Äôm letting yet another man chip away a part of me when, honestly, i don‚Äôt have any more pieces left to give.
sometimes i wish i could throw away the past and become a new me. a girl who didn‚Äôt crave so much validation. a girl who didn‚Äôt burn every bridge from fear of rejection. a girl who without a shadow of a doubt knew her worth. 
but beyond my scars, who am i really? i am an ambitious, loving, and free-spirited beam of light. i‚Äôm a force to be reckoned with, a dreamer. i‚Äôm forever learning, forever evolving, and full of life. i‚Äôm a beautiful, courageous, and gloriously authentic work in progress. 
while my past is indeed a part of me, it in no way encompasses who i am or who i‚Äôm meant to be. i‚Äôve had my trials and tribulations. i‚Äôve gone through my phases. i‚Äôve been my own worst enemy. 
yet in spite of it all here i am with the nerve to accept all that is me. i forgive myself for not giving the self-love i needed so desperately. i forgive myself for accepting less than i deserve. i forgive myself for not being the girl i wished i could be. and honestly, thank god i‚Äôm not her and she‚Äôs not me. because she‚Äôs a fantasy and i‚Äôm real as can be.

text:
her
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
on the morning of thursday, september 27th, 2018, an eager anticipation woke us up in our brooklyn loft unusually early. with our hearts racing, we tuned into the hearings of dr. christine blasey ford and judge brett kavanaugh.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
amidst dr. ford‚Äôs emotionally brave testimony, kavanaugh‚Äôs flippant denial, and an amalgamation of statements from an assembly of both incredibly compassionate and unbelievably ruthless senators, we made a new song. and it was for her.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
once the hearings were over, we began putting a video together to more fully capture the inspiration behind this song. we wanted to point to women, from a range of walks of life, women who have taken a stance when it wasn‚Äôt necessarily easy to do so. our goal was to highlight the courage it takes to call something out loud and to stand up tall when the odds may not be in our favor.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
the women in this piece are just a few among many who inspire us to continue to use our voices and demand to be heard. the conclusory chorus lyric ‚Äúnever look back again‚Äù doesn‚Äôt imply we shouldn‚Äôt look back on the women who have taught us how to lead the way ‚Äî we most absolutely should ‚Äî but that we should always move bravely into the future. we hope with our song to thank the women who have empowered us so selflessly and perhaps to inspire those still searching to find their strengths.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
see the full video for ‚Äúher‚Äù now ‚Äî link in bio.

music and lyrics by gracie and rachel @gracieandrachel 
co-written and co-produced by garrett eaton @the_name_is_dame
mixed by steve wall @swallja

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
on the morning of thursday, september 27th, 2018, an eager anticipation woke us up in our brooklyn loft unusually early. with our hearts racing, we tuned into the hearings of dr. christine blasey ford and judge brett kavanaugh.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
amidst dr. ford‚Äôs emotionally brave testimony, kavanaugh‚Äôs flippant denial, and an amalgamation of statements from an assembly of both incredibly compassionate and unbelievably ruthless senators, we made a new song. and it was for her.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
once the hearings were over, we began putting a video together to more fully capture the inspiration behind this song. we wanted to point to women, from a range of walks of life, women who have taken a stance when it wasn‚Äôt necessarily easy to do so. our goal was to highlight the courage it takes to call something out loud and to stand up tall when the odds may not be in our favor.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
the women in this piece are just a few among many who inspire us to continue to use our voices and demand to be heard. the conclusory chorus lyric ‚Äúnever look back again‚Äù doesn‚Äôt imply we shouldn‚Äôt look back on the women who have taught us how to lead the way ‚Äî we most absolutely should ‚Äî but that we should always move bravely into the future. we hope with our song to thank the women who have empowered us so selflessly and perhaps to inspire those still searching to find their strengths.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî

text:
strength and perseverance on your healing journey.
.
.
.
 the recent rulings may seem like a set back but we have come a long way since the beginning of our fight. like most things in life, there is no end, only growth. continual battles. if we keep insisting on betterment then it will happen. if we all hold our neighbor accountable when we see them perpetuating abusive and oppressive behaviors we can make great leaps in social progress. .
 these are the things that i need to tell myself to feel better. i don‚Äôt regularly enough. my inner voice is one majoritively of doubt and self loathing. i get so overwhelmed by news like there being no justice for christine blasey ford, and another rapist being given great power. if there is none for a straight, cis, successful, professional, educated white woman, there is absolutely none for the marginalized woman.  because of my ptsd from past abuse i completely shut down. shut everyone out. i feel like i can barely control my body movements at times. my heart feels like it might explode. i want to run. i cry, and sit with the fact that my body means nothing to men in our society. my identity is only what i physically appear to be. i am a thing. i am to serve men‚Äôs needs. i sit, and my throat burns, and i want to set the world on fire. .
.
.

text:
sooo fun fact, i‚Äôve been studying #asl - american sign language over the last few weeks - i still have a ways to go but this sign symbol for ‚Äòokay‚Äô resonates so strongly for me given our current political scene, #metoo movement, my personal life, and as the most simplistic way to communicate. okay, can imply so much and so little which makes this hand gesture and word so powerful. okay can mean; authorization or approval, satisfactory, agreement, or indifference. it is also one of the most frequently spoken and written words on the planet! psa for the more you know. even at its most simplistic form this word and gesture can communicate so much.
‚à¥
okay for me today means ... it‚Äôs ok to rest, it‚Äôs ok to stand up for myself and others. i‚Äôm ok with going the extra mile to make a difference. pie for lunch? ok. am i ok today? are you ok? is it ok for me to help you?
‚à¥

text:
‚Äúthere‚Äôs part of me
that‚Äôs banging on the walls 
of the cage that is my body
screaming, clawing
trying not to drown
begging for someone
anyone
to listen 
no matter how hard i try 
to scrub away the fingerprints left so violently on me
you can still feel the residue 
of their blistering hands 
you can still see the scars 
you could say i was a bird
who knows its wings are broken 
but can still be found
barreling off of buildings 
i am cotton candy softness 
melts in the palm of your hand
sugar sweet,
i‚Äôll rot your teeth
watch me detonate 
i‚Äôll burn your cities to the ground 
this heart is a haunted house 
and these chains have names
guilt and shame 
and fear clamped tight around my throat
i still wake to tiptoed footsteps 
and jump at the slightest sounds
but i am a force of nature
and my power knows no bounds.‚Äù i wanted to save this for my second book, but with everything going on i really felt it on my heart share. i originally wrote this about the way i was feeling and by the time i was done i realized it wasn‚Äôt simply my own anymore, but someone very close to me. this is ‚Äúthis heart is a haunted house.‚Äù photo creds: @drawnbymary

i‚Äôm reposting this beautiful soul‚Äôs words...please read.
#repost @beetlemeier_too with @get_repost
„Éª„Éª„Éª
i was reflecting on the audience of people who follow me, and noticing how few men do. with the news filled with revolting displays of unchecked masculinity, i keep looking for examples of men standing up for women. for the most part i‚Äôm not finding it. which is both not surprising, and also profoundly disappointing. 
i had a man explain to me that he doesn‚Äôt hire women for his business because he‚Äôs worried about the #metoo movement. he thinks it‚Äôs too big of a risk to hire women right now (instead of holding the male employees accountable?!?) i really tried to keep my cool as i asked him if he understood that he was describing to me how he is actively discriminating against women. he didn‚Äôt. and this problem that anyone should have to deal with what men make women deal with every day is fucking exponentially compounded if the person is a poc or lgbtqia. 
so when i hear talks or see memes with messages like ‚Äúmen are trash‚Äù or something poking at white fragility... i have to agree. i repost them. i use them in conversations. just because there are a few good eggs, it doesn‚Äôt excuse the heaps of garbage they‚Äôre buried in. 
if you didn‚Äôt want people to talk about all the shit you‚Äôve done, then you should have been a better person, and you‚Äôre going to reap what you sow. i think this makes most men very uncomfortable around me. and it should. i‚Äôm the feminist you were warned about. i‚Äôm the one that kicks dirt on your boys party. i‚Äôm the one that calls you out on your ‚Äúlocker room talk‚Äù. because you‚Äôve made me uncomfortable my whole life, and tried to make me feel guilty about it. tried to shame me for not being one of the guys; one of the guys that degrades both women and men for not relishing in the privileges of the patriarchy. 
no more. i was never on your side. üéÉüéÉüéÉüéÉüéÉüéÉüéÉüéÉüéÉüéÉ
also, here‚Äôs some jack-o-lanterns and a picture of me in flowery leggings and a pink hat at dollywood.

i had a man explain to me that he doesn‚Äôt hire women for his business because he‚Äôs worried about the  movement. he thinks it‚Äôs too big of a risk to hire women right now (instead of holding the male employees accountable?!?) i really tried to keep my cool as i asked him if he understood that he was describing to me how he is actively discriminating against women. he didn‚Äôt. and this problem that anyone should have to deal with what men make women deal with every day is fucking exponentially compounded if the person is a poc or lgbtqia. 
so when i hear talks or see memes with messages like ‚Äúmen are trash‚Äù or something poking at white fragility... i have to agree. i repost them. i use them in conversations. just because there are a few good eggs, it doesn‚Äôt excuse the heaps of garbage they‚Äôre buried in.

no more. i was never on your side. üéÉüéÉüéÉüéÉüéÉüéÉüéÉüéÉüéÉüéÉ

text:
october is #domesticviolenceawarenessmonth and we‚Äôll be sharing some stats/info about how domestic violence affects those around us, especially women of color. 
domestic violence is a pattern of behaviors used by one partner to maintain power and control over another partner in an intimate relationship. 
check out the power & control wheel to learn about various types of abuse and tactics used, such as: 
emotional abuse
economic abuse
using children 
using isolation
using male privilege 
and more...
*although this wheel uses she/her pronouns for the victim and assumes a male perpetrator, it‚Äôs important to remember that abuse can happen to people of any gender in any type of relationship. [wheel by the domestic abuse intervention project] 
______
shoutout to domestic violence survivors everywhere. we support you. we love you. we believe you. 
@domesticvictors @abuse_warriors @domesticworkers

#repost @mariannewilliamson
„Éª„Éª„Éª
we heal through a kind of detox, not just physically but societally as well. everything has got to come up in order to be released. and god knows, our dregs are coming up now. more than anything else at present is the deep misogyny at the heart of our culture. re-watching the anita hill hearings on television the other day, i almost become nauseated. and here we are, almost 30 years later, with the same kinds of men planning to ram down our throats (perfect image) the candidate that best suits their corporatocracy- over-democracy scheme, ready to smear the woman whose truth would argue against it. on one hand, even if they withdraw brett kavanaugh‚Äôs nomination there will be someone next on the list who represents the same kind of judicial philosophy. but that is not what matters most here. what matters is that we refuse to ignore the significance of sexual assault - we simply refuse - and no it is not less significant because he was in high school. the last thing we need is to send a message to the teenage boys of america, ‚Äúit‚Äôs ok if you do this kids, just knock it off when you‚Äôre older.‚Äù between our delayed reaction to trump‚Äôs misogyny in the 2016 presidential campaign, the #metoo movement and our own experiences, so many american women  are just sick and tired of this. it has simply got to end. we can‚Äôt give birth to a more light-filled era, we can‚Äôt say ‚Äúyes‚Äù to higher possibilities for humanity, unless we‚Äôre willing to say a fierce, firm, and loving ‚Äúno‚Äù to the shadows of the past. in honor of our grandmothers and for the sake of our granddaughters, it‚Äôs time.

text:
chairman chuck grassley's october 2nd, 2018 letter to dr. christine blasey ford's legal team. 
_
it would appear that the alleged victim's legal team isn't providing important requested details to the senate judiciary committee. you would assume they would be as candid and transparent as possible since the burden of proof is on the accuser... not the accused. remember when they requested that kavanaugh testify first-- before his accuser? these people are really trying to strong-arm basic judicial procedure and due process. i don't know about you, but i wouldn't want to live in a country where you guilty until proven innocent! like i said in my most recent article (link in the bio), pay close attention to both parties reactions and responses as we navigate through this conundrum. üëÄü§∑üèΩ‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏èüôèüèΩ
_

text:
my hope comes from the lord. 
i have learned over the years how to tackle the battles of life with a sound peace and strength, from the lord. 
things do not always go our way, but my confidence is in that christ has a greater plan than my own.  my confidence is in god and not the situation. my faith is in him, not what is seen. 
i can remain hopeful, because i know there are more for me than against me. 
i know that the lord does not allow evil to win. 
i know that as i persevere, truth will come to light, in his timing. 
today i remain hopeful, and at peace in the battle. 
our god is greater, he is mighty, and he fights my battles ! ‚Ä¢

text:
i could not sleep last night. over and over again i just kept thinking this is the exact reason that sexual assault victims do not come forward. they are afraid of being mocked, laughed at, shamed, and ridiculed. just as our president did yesterday at a campaign rally in mississippi. trump is lashing out at not only professor ford but the entire #metoo movement, which got its start when a known sexual predator was elected president. ‚ôÄ
during his rant trump talked of the innocent men being falsely accused of sexual harassment and suffering for it. ‚Äúthink of your husbands,‚Äù trump told the women in the crowd, who cheered him. ‚Äúthink of your sons.‚Äù at one point, trump mimicked a son asking his mom for advice on how to respond to a false accusation. ‚Äúit‚Äôs a damn sad situation,‚Äù he said.
‚ôÄ
should we be surprised? of course not. the more guilty he is of something the harder he pushes back  his advice to men accused of sexual assault? ‚Äúyou‚Äôve got to deny, deny, deny and push back on these women. if you admit to anything and any culpability, then you‚Äôre dead. you‚Äôve got to be strong. you‚Äôve got to be aggressive. you‚Äôve got to push back hard. you‚Äôve got to deny anything that‚Äôs said about you. never admit.‚Äù
‚ôÄ
and as always his claims, ideas, and beliefs have zero basis in reality. studies have shown over and over again that false claims make up only a miniscule  percentage of reported assaults. and most assaults, of course, aren‚Äôt reported at all. i wonder why. ‚ôÄ

text:
jumping in on this challenge because i love this stretch, even though i‚Äôve really been struggling with my flexibility. i blame donald trump. that‚Äôs a half-joke. in some ways, it‚Äôs the absolute truth. i‚Äôm a pretty guarded person as it is and when i see the president mock a victim of sexual assault, i want to curl up into a little ball and stay there. i‚Äôm in awe of those women who have shared their #metoo stories of harassment and posted about their histories of sexual assault. i‚Äôm sure that it is cathartic. i have more stories than i could begin to share in a post and am the victim of assault myself. but, don‚Äôt worry‚Ä¶ i won‚Äôt be sharing them anytime soon. my instinct is to keep it close. it‚Äôs been interesting to see that play out in my practice and maybe it‚Äôs a mistake, but i‚Äôm not fighting it. i‚Äôm trying to just let it be and have faith that the day will come again where i feel safe enough to open up my heart and body again.

text_retweet:
i‚Äôve never posted my own content before, but i think if ever there was a time, this message is important to spread. feel free to share as well! 
#repost @beetlemeier_too with @get_repost
„Éª„Éª„Éª
i was reflecting on the audience of people who follow me, and noticing how few men do. with the news filled with revolting displays of unchecked masculinity, i keep looking for examples of men standing up for women. for the most part i‚Äôm not finding it. which is both not surprising, and also profoundly disappointing. 
i had a man explain to me that he doesn‚Äôt hire women for his business because he‚Äôs worried about the #metoo movement. he thinks it‚Äôs too big of a risk to hire women right now (instead of holding the male employees accountable?!?) i really tried to keep my cool as i asked him if he understood that he was describing to me how he is actively discriminating against women. he didn‚Äôt. and this problem that anyone should have to deal with what men make women deal with every day is fucking exponentially compounded if the person is a poc or lgbtqia. 
so when i hear talks or see memes with messages like ‚Äúmen are trash‚Äù or something poking at white fragility... i have to agree. i repost them. i use them in conversations. just because there are a few good eggs, it doesn‚Äôt excuse the heaps of garbage they‚Äôre buried in. 
if you didn‚Äôt want people to talk about all the shit you‚Äôve done, then you should have been a better person, and you‚Äôre going to reap what you sow. i think this makes most men very uncomfortable around me. and it should. i‚Äôm the feminist you were warned about. i‚Äôm the one that kicks dirt on your boys party. i‚Äôm the one that calls you out on your ‚Äúlocker room talk‚Äù. because you‚Äôve made me uncomfortable my whole life, and tried to make me feel guilty about it. tried to shame me for not being one of the guys; one of the guys that degrades both women and men for not relishing in the privileges of the patriarchy. 
no more. i was never on your side. üéÉüéÉüéÉüéÉüéÉüéÉüéÉüéÉüéÉüéÉ
also, here‚Äôs some jack-o-lanterns and a picture of me in flowery leggings and a pink hat at dollywood.

text:
it isn't that people "don't believe victims of sexual assault or abuse"
because that isn't true. 
if i know and can see real evidence, real proof; if you can show me that it happened, i believe you.

but we are innocent until proven guilty.
of any crime.
because it is our protection. because people do lie. because people do manipulate things for their gain. because people can be motivated by guilt or regret, or they may want to make a statement and don't know a better way. because no one should be able to just say something and it be seen as fact, for anything. 
because your emotional response isn't proof.
because your past experience does not determine this one.
because you don't get to make an example of someone who did nothing wrong, simply because you didn't do what you should have to begin with.
because the presumption of guilt can devastate entire lives.
because two wrongs don't make a right. so telling me "well it happened to her and the justice system failed her" doesn't mean it should fail someone else.
because the actual problem needs to be addressed and handled right, not covered with the bandaid of some new, potentially innocent bandaid.

you don't get to look at the claim being made and decide, without any real evidence, that someone is guilty beyond reasonable doubt because you are biased by gender or your own past.

you have to ask the hard questions. you have to look at the full story. you have to have something real to show.

you do have responsibility of your own to take care of yourself. go to the cops, answer the hard questions, do the hard tests, and follow the system. don't wait 20 years to decide you want to get back at someone. take the steps put in order to make the community a safer place for yourself and everyone else. there are channels for protection. 
i get that it is hard. so is finding out you could have prevented the rape after you. so is seeing the person after you do what you couldn't and win. 
i know it is scary to think you may not have enough evidence or that you won't be believed. so is having to watch your back and your friends back for the rest of your life because one day he might return  worse than before.

our newest blog article tackles the very sensitive climate of me too, political polarization and loving our neighbor no matter what. this is a perspective we don‚Äôt often see, but one that is needed if we wish to live harmoniously with those whose opinions we do not share. here‚Äôs an excerpt: ‚Äúi do not know how i will feel if judge kavanaugh is appointed to the supreme court, but i do know that i cannot, in truth, separate myself from those whom i disagree with. i cannot treat them as if they are wrong and i am right, and i cannot say they are not my brothers and sisters‚Äìno matter how unhinged i may think they are. this is how i intend to survive the #metoo era‚Äìarm in arm with my allies and my enemies alike.‚Äù
.

text: the hometown series iii: it was the churches gym room floor. i sat there numb to everything that played out that summer. week after week, it was something after the other and i couldn‚Äôt catch my breath. i was 14, about to go into my freshmen year and it felt like the huger games. two weeks before i sat there, a guy tried to rape me in the backyard of a random house. i never showed interest in this guy. i never kissed this guy. i never anything with this guy. and even if i had, it doesn‚Äôt matter. it all happened so fast and i was literally stunned. he pushed me on the wet grass, dropped his pants and i immediately was like, no, i am not doing this with you. he was persistent and aggressive and at this point i was completely panicking. i heard footsteps from the street behind us, and jumped up so fast and sprinted as i tried to get my pants on, and was met by my now brother in love, kyle. he saw i was a mess and gave me a hug and started to walk me down the street. that‚Äôs when he and i became best friends. troy was on the phone with his then girlfriend, and whenever he hung up he came and sat next to me on that gym floor. i‚Äôd seen him around, but all i knew was he was kyle‚Äôs brother and he wore a gray hoodie a lot. we talked all night and he was so different then the rest. i had sworn off ever getting married, and after that night i looked at my sister and said ‚Äúi‚Äôm going to marry him.‚Äù we all became really close friends, and through the whispers on the bleachers, and the things people said about me in the halls, he somehow still fell in love with me. he got to me as fast as he could, and wasn‚Äôt afraid of my wild heart. he knew my mind inside and out, and wasn‚Äôt scared of it. we fell hard and fast, and were just so in love. it was pure, while being rebellious and definitely worth all the trials we knew we would face. one of my favorite things about this place is how god wrote our love story amidst disaster. he gave me and us grace time after time. i am so undeserving that i got to keep the best thing that was ever in that town, but here we are. i‚Äôll happily wear the title ‚Äúsinclairs sweetheart‚Äù on the back of my shirt foreverüåπ

text:

text:
yesterday was october 2üçÅüéÉüëªmy favorite month and lucky number. yesterday was also the day i took two huge steps forward to make me healthier, it‚Äôs steps forward to figure out what i am fighting. i had my first psychiatrist appointment and an mri appointment. i was looking forward to both but i was also very anxious and afraid. afraid that they might not end up being able to tell me what is wrong, like the dr.‚Äôs in the past. but i tried to stay positive. and after both appointment i did feel relieved, although it‚Äôs too early to diagnose my physical or mental issues yet. i felt better knowing that i made the right decision to bring in professional help on the mental side and more professional help on the physical side.
üé°
after my mri, andrew took me to the fall fest for some yummies and to walk through the rides and games and just have a small escape from reality. of course we got a jug of apple cider and we had a pork ‚Äòn‚Äô beans parfait, deep fried mac n cheese and corn dogs made with pancake batter, but this year i tried my first deep fried twinkie ü§§üòç, just saying. thanks for all that bee!

text:
please share.

this ironically hits #thebeinginbusiness day 21 and domestic abuse awareness month day 3.

i have waited 6 years to publicly say this and i know people will disapprove and disapprove of it being on my business page, but this is my public voice and i'm using it.

my husband is a good, loving man, he's the sort of man who turns down a drunken woman (me) when she throws herself at him and i love him with all of my heart.

i would never ask him to perjure himself in crown court for some wierd evil step mother reason because that would be to ask him to do something reprehensible that would fundamentally damage his soul and our relationship.

during that trial i was 5 and a half months pregnant which is hardly indicative of a failing marriage.

we have a relationship built on a solid bedrock of absolute trust and honesty.

i have spoken to hundreds if not thousands of victims of domestic violence and abuse and the common thread is how people turn a blind eye or excuse an abuser or believe a victim is lying.

this all normalises abuse - it's takes a strong, extraordinary person to stand up and say - you did the wrong thing and i love you too much to tell you what you did is ok.

i also owe it to the wider world to tell my truth.

my husband was this strong, extraordinary person, he paid a massive personal cost, he lost his past, some of his family and any future grandchildren - those grandchildren have also lost their right to a relationship with an amazing human based on a pack of lies and peoples willingness to turn a blind eye to abuse.

i'm so proud of my husband and i love him with all of my heart and i only wish there were more men in the world like him.

so it is him i admire the most. he's held me up, picked me up, walks with me and supports me with unconditional love and i do the same back.

#love #marriage #survivor #whyileft #whyistayed #domesticviolence #survivorspeaks #metoo #livefearfree #domesticabuse #womensaid #nspcc  #harrispye #father #husband #pride #love #trust #truth #mamabear #empoweredwoman #wife #mother #harrispye
@thewhitethistle @thefreestylecoach

text:
there are calls in south africa for convicted rapists to be castrated.
‚Ä¶
south africa has one of the highest incidences of rape in the world. and recently a trial has started for a man alleged to have raped a seven-year-old girl in a restaurant toilet.
‚Ä¶
now the women's league of south africa's governing anc party has pushed for extreme action on the issue. the president of the league says the use of drugs to curb the libido, should be explored, but "any form of castration" should be considered.
‚Ä¶
but what do you think? is this too extreme? or does there need to be a wider cultural change?

text:
those days where you want to hide, ever have them?!! life isn‚Äôt always enthusiasm and positivity, love hearts and roses, smiles and niceties. 
days can be tough, with challenges, relationship problems, issues with kids, conflict, wobbly self esteem, financial worries, mental health difficulties... it‚Äôs all part of life right? 
what do i do in a place of discomfort? i do my best to get through that moment. afterwards i might cry, rant or withdraw. i let myself feel whatever i need to feel and try to talk about it as honestly as i can. 
i know that i need a couple of days to let myself just be in this place as my mind processes and adjusts. 
i need to up my self care, rest and exercise. i need to be really kind to myself and surround myself with the right support. 
i need to let myself think but not ruminate. i need to examine the problem and work out my options. 
when i notice i‚Äôm obsessing and being unrealistic or irrational i try to let it go, with the faith that i will find a way through. my mind is working out the pros and cons and all of the possible solution, and in a few days i‚Äôll have clarity. i‚Äôll feel better, more able to manage the problem, and i can get on with it again.

i know this is my pattern and i accept it. what‚Äôs your pattern and what do you need to do to look after yourself and find your answers? #reallife #challenge #problems #solutions #youcandoit #dontgiveup #mentalwellbeing #proactive #selfcare #findsupport #occupationaltherapy #practicalmindset #metoo ‚ù§Ô∏è

text: the antidote to collapsing into hopelessness is rage. üå± though i tried to avoid the clip of the so-called potus mocking ‚Äî actually mocking!!!!!! ‚Äî dr. ford, i haven‚Äôt been able to. and appalled is too weak a word. what i imagine is millions of girls and women closing their mouths to the truth they were getting close to speaking. i imagine every young girl who hasn‚Äôt been able to tell what was done to her seeing that, and then within me there is a click of time that offers a choice: i can sink into the hopelessness of that, or i can allow the rage to volcano up through the top of my head! we‚Äôre at a pivot time right now. nothing like this has ever happened. even bannon is afraid of the fall of patriarchy now. rage is cleansing, propelling, it runs the engine of revolution, it gets us out the door and away from the abuser, it launches the solution and gives rise to poem and painting. rage is creative. rage is a beautiful fire. rage is both the fire and the fuel. we can watch it move through us, being curious about its sensations in the body. observe it. flow with it. rage is not violence. violence is violence. violence can be cold as hell. we can reject violence and feel our rage. women, we must. we must stop listening to the narrative of the patriarchs which tells us that rage does not become us. why is that narrative there? for 10,000 years? so that we won‚Äôt fight back. and suppressing our rage is crippling. it leads to illness and depression. so let‚Äôs feel it. it‚Äôs time. we‚Äôre here. #rage #rageagainstpatriarchy #fuckno #fight #change #metoo #ibelieveher #selfcare #mentalhealth #trauma #healing

text:
do you?
.
.
there are so many reasons why women who suffer harassment don‚Äôt come forward. in fact, why only women, men too. .
.
shame, fear of consequences, the million dollar question of who‚Äôs even going to believe them are just some of the reasons why. it takes a lot of courage for survivors to speak about what happened to them. it takes a lot of courage to revisit those dreadful memories. emotional and mental trauma aside, the fear that nothing will happen to the perpetrators of the crime, makes the experience even more nerve wracking. .
.
so, a human being, a fairly decent one atleast, all you need to do is listen to them, hear them out and not taint their effort with abuses. not that hard to do that, right? afterall, only if you create an environment conducive to survivors speaking up can more people come forward and maybe something can be done eventually about making this world safe for us!
.
.
what do you say?
.
.

text: almost two years ago now, i was raped on a college campus. i wrote an essay about one of the ways in which it has impacted my life. the publication womens wire weekly, based out of dc, has given me the opportunity to share my story using their platform. the link is in my bio if you would like to give it a read. and to all of the women who have had to relieve their trauma day in and day out since the kavanaugh hearings have began (and this presidency)- i stand with you and i love you. please reach out if you are survivor and need help. remember, we belong to each other.  #metoo #timesup

text: abuse is a one on one experience, but what causes abuse to be perpetrated is so much deeper. so much bigger than the individual(s) and shame can keep abusers and abused in a pattern that continues, we must create new ways to allow ourselves to be seen and heard without believing narratives of unworthiness. the oppressive patterns in us must be seen and remedied; believing someone is either one thing or another, good v. bad is a place i see these unnatural and imposed constructs feeding the cycle this is the essence of the holding grasp of these constructs that are not of human form, but of the mind. believing that something is good or bad and nothing else is denying the truth, and informs and perpetuates the cycles of shame and oppression. it denies that those who do wrong are unworthy of love, respect, and healing. the patriarchy, whiteness, fascism, & colonialism are constructs that regardless of who you are, if you grew up in this culture are inevitable, in informing our reality, and it is all of our individual jobs to dismantle these internal symptoms of oppression that live inside us all. we must not use the same ailments of oppression to prove our points or ourselves; it is not our choice to force others to open, and love is the way it is just more complicated than we hold in our understanding. hierarchy is a construct of these ideas as well, there is no better or worse than. no one is unworthy, and it is no ones job to make another look within at these constructs. it is our own voyage, and to be there to aid those willing and wanting to do that work. we cannot change these constructs and narratives without recognizing our own constructs of fascism, without wrangling our own entitlement. with a great honoring the most powerful aspects of true non attachment and highest forms of love.  #patriarchy #loveconquers #healing #whiteness #domesticabusesurvivor #survivor #metoo #inclusion #earth #earthcare #peoplecare

text:
if you thought domestic violence was a woman only problem, think again. men fall victim to abuse everyday. have you heard a woman say "he does what i say!" "he can't see the kids" or "he gives me his check and i give him an allowance" all those things are abuse. many men fall victim to verbal and emotional abuse. it is easy for a good man to be abused because they are taught to not defend themselves against women. if we stand with survivors, we have to stand with all survivors. women are abusers too, domestic abuse has no gender.
.

text:
i was raped when i was 18 years old on october 26th, 2012.
i reported it 1 year and 3 days later.
my life, is still in tatters.
my life, is still shattered. 
his isn't.
i wasnt going to share this post today. in fact, i don't know if i was ever going to post this. but quite frankly, im so enraged by our "president", that i feel the need to speak my voice because no one talks about the aftermath. no one talks about what happens after "boys will be boys". so i'm going to talk about it.
being raped ruined my life.
i was just over a month into my freshman year at the university of iowa on a full ride scholarship. i was hoping to major in biology.
i had potential and i never thought the mandatory sexual assault awareness online class would apply to me.
he was a close friend for 7 years.
the next day when he dropped me off at my dorm and told me to tell no one, i showered for 4 hours. i couldnt scrub him away.
i was now a tattered woman.
every day i:
-repeated the event in my mind
-showered for hours
-cut/scratch myself
-deprived myself of food bc i believed i didnt deserve to eat
-got off the dorm elevator if a man joined until i could ride alone
-avoided all contact with men
-cry until 5am in the stairwell
-would skip class to sleep during the day
for 5 months i didnt sleep at night out of fear i would wake up to him on top of me.
for 1 year id imagine killing myself.
1.5 years later i moved states and left my scholarship bc i couldnt handle the harassment and living a block from his parents house.
for 1.5 years i didnt eat more than a can of soup or package of pasta every couple of days or would throw away food given to me.
for 4 years i would hurt myself.
5 years later i would finally finish a drink.
it's been almost 6 years and ive thought about it every single day.
i still cry. i can still picture him in his black hoodie. i can still feel him on my skin.
i went through 2 extremely abusive relationships since bc hey, they werent raping me so everything else seemed like love.
my sense of self was destroyed.
i lost all of my friends. my relationships within my family were forever changed and ruined. i still fear men. im still shattered.
fuck this administration.

text:
this little piggy is taking men to task. 
18‚Äùx24‚Äù

ink/paper

the good ol‚Äô boys club just wants women to be quiet, don‚Äôt speak up, don‚Äôt have a voice, don‚Äôt have independent thought and definitely don‚Äôt be in a power position. they want to keep you tied up and quiet. 
it has infuriated #misspiggy and she will transform herself and find her voice!
miss piggy will forever be changed. 
speak up. unite. demand equality and respect. 
do not be silent! 
arguably a top indelible image and first cartoon/puppet character of our childhood years. 
a mere part of a larger series of artworks that were to be, and are, my commentary on where it seems our country, society and culture is today compared to when i was a child. 
the crux of the series is based on childhood cartoons and characters that i had grown up with and that represent my childhood. now, these characters are distorted into something that will never, at least unlikely, be the same again. they used to be sharp, clean lines and brightly colored.... now they are rough, dirty, twisted and in black and white. 
i hope you like it. it is also a bit of therapy for me realizing a dealing with the state of our country right now.

text:
while stopped on the side of a particularly challenging 4x4 trail, engineer pass, our vehicles were passed by a jeep driven by a male. his window was down, so i gave a courteous wave. ‚Äúkudos young lady, from california‚Äù he said to me, while driving past my two male friends without comment. his tone implied he was surprised to see a woman complete that trail. initially i was stunned, but i have spent most of my life on the receiving end of comments such as these and have sadly becoming accustomed to hearing statements like these. in the beginning they wore me down, but eventually these words simply drove me to become a stronger woman.
.
to the man in the jeep, and any other man who makes sexist comments such as these, it is not acceptable.
.
yes i completed that trail.
yes this 4runner is my car.
yes i love off-roading.
yes i am a badass woman.
.

i opened this page with the sole purpose of sharing biological and scientific facts about women's bodies. because there are so many - too many - things that we don't know, that we are not educated about... i am not even talking about political or social awareness here, but about our health! 
i wanted to share something that matters to all women (and men) regardless of their country, political opinion, the color of their skin or their religion. 
but sometimes i feel so upset and angry with local and international news, that i eventually decided not to hold back, at least on instagram.
the #knowledgeablewomen facebook page will keep its focus on being dedicated to health education, but right now i need this page to be a space where i can share more. .
.

text: so according to the president, it‚Äôs a scary time for young men right now. while i agree that there are women who falsely accuse men of sexual assault/rape, there are also men who are sexually assaulting/raping women and getting away with it because those women are too afraid, ashamed and embarrassed to speak up. they live with their secret for years creating deep wounds that affect their lives and relationships. it‚Äôs not until they speak up that they can finally start the healing process. for someone to try and take that away from them is a disgrace. if it‚Äôs a scary time for young men then what kind of time is it for young women? young women whose choice was taken away, whose bodies were violated, who were forced to live in a dark place of fear and whose spirits were crushed. young women who had no choice but to believe that they did something wrong, something to deserve this, just so that they wouldn‚Äôt have to relive that horrible moment by telling someone. i applaud the women who are brave enough to face their assailants and speak their truth and i admire their strength. you are important, you matter and you are loved. speak your truth because only when the darkness is exposed to light, can we overcome it. ‚ù§Ô∏è #metoo

text:
let‚Äôs meet 4 more of our speakers! ‚ú®
.
@__andrea.marie__ is a black feminist, pisces, and doctoral student in african american and african diaspora studies (aaads) at indiana university-bloomington. she presently serves as the political education committee chair of the black graduate student association. learn more about andrea during saturday's black women‚Äôs experiences from 10 - 11 am!
.
@cslaughters is a multi-hyphenate: writer, director and voiceover. she produced and acted in new york and london theater collaborating with writers like beau willimon (house of cards), elizabeth meriwether (new girl) and annie baker (pulitzer prize winner of the flick). she is currently focused on film/tv development in georgia and recently wrapped lamb (which will be shown friday from 10 - 11 am), a film about the female assistants who led the victims up to harvey weinstein‚Äôs hotel room, which she and her producing team will use as a vehicle to support the #metoo and #timesup movement.
.
@symkinney is a fiction writer and beer enthusiast. after earning her bachelor‚Äôs in creative writing from indiana university, she continued to live in bloomington to write her novel, an untitled work of historical fiction. she is experienced in the bar and restaurant industry, taking pride in the ins and outs of hospitality, the impact of food and liquor in relationships, and has plans to open her own food business in the near future. find sym with andrea at saturday's black women's experiences!
.
and last, but not least, meet @danielle7185 ! - "growing up in the country, being outdoors was always second nature to me. living in the fast-paced digital age we live in today i realized that there was a need for more people to unplug from technology and reconnect with themselves in nature. this was one of the many reasons why kate (my wife) and i founded dnk presents. together we have organized and guided hundreds of people on adventures in and outside of indiana. i am blessed to share my passion for the great outdoors while helping individuals and groups build confidence and empowerment through adventure experiences."
.

.
.
new hires must be trained within the first six months, and employees must receive an hour of training while managers/supervisors must still receive two.
.
.

text:
how to be an ally to survivors;
‚Ä¢ believe them
‚Ä¢ listen to what they say and respect their boundaries
‚Ä¢ refrain from asking invasive questions
‚Ä¢ be patient

text:
we invite you to join our solidarity vigil #cancelkavanaugh on thursday, october 4th! we will meet on the west steps of the capitol at 5:30 p.m.
.

5:30 p.m. - speaker line-up and survivor testimonies 
6:30 p.m. - candle light vigil honoring survivors 
wear red and black
.

tea lights and led lights are welcome during the vigil.
.

this event will have asl interpreters during the speaker portion of the gathering. 
kavanaugh has shown that he is hostile to women‚Äîfrom his record against women's health and autonomy to his record against workplace protections to the sexual assault allegations against him to the anger he displayed to female u.s. senators.
.
kavanaugh has shown that he has no credibility: he has lied repeatedly in confirmation hearings spanning two decades, and he lied again in his testimony regarding dr. christine blasey ford's credible allegation of sexual assault.
.
now is the time for all of us to come together and tell our senators to believe women and stop kavanaugh this week‚Äîand to show the country that women, and all of us, will hold republicans accountable on november 6.
.

kavanaugh would rule for a generation against reproductive freedom, health care, the environment, voting rights, workers‚Äô rights, lgbtq rights, and immigrant rights, while siding with big corporations, big money, and the trump agenda. and we can't let the white house rush and hamper an fbi investigation. the survivors who have stepped forward in recent weeks deserve better, as do we all.
.

senators in all fifty states must listen to their constituents, do their jobs to uphold the will of the people, protect the soul of our country and constitution, and block this nomination. together, we will fight to ensure brett kavanaugh never gets confirmed by the senate. we will #stopkavanaugh. join us.
.

text:
i found more pictures btw.
im opening up about this piece a little bit more, aside from it being performative art.
.
.
there are two parts to this piece, the background was done in 2014, the heart i did this year for another reason.
.
. 
all the words on this piece of wood is from one of my exes. he pretended to be a stranger on the internet on multiple different fb accounts and then had the nerve to try to get me back. .
.
i had to make it into a piece because at the end of the day, for my well being, i needed to let go of all the anxiety and anger i was carrying.
.
.
i covered those words with paint using my feet and hands while i talked about how shitty he is
.
.
honestly, it helped me heal so much and feel empowered. but then i put it away because i still wasn't ready to share my experience.  the only who knew were those in class with me
.
.
#heart #art #chicago #chicagoart #sexualharassment #metoo #acrylicpaint #acrylic #paint #cw #artheals #arttherapy  #womenempowerment #empowerment

text:
final thoughts on consent.....
parents have a tremendous responsibility as their child's first teachers. however, we have overlooked some extremely important topics because to a great degree, many parents didn't understand their importance while others assumed their child "knew better", and others may not have been educated about the topics themselves. these include boundaries, body autonomy and of course, consent. these conversations must start early and be reiterated constantly by incorporating additional age appropriate information to ensure your child has a complete grasp on how they are expected to engage others regardless of the nature of their relationship. your child should know that permission is always required for anyone to touch them, and for them to touch anyone else be it casually and ultimately, sexually. as your child matures into adolescence, they should be fully aware that self control is mandatory and their desire for sexual satisfaction does not override the need for permission to engage another person in any sexual contact. your child should know that the absence of consent/permission is considered assault and that can and should have consequences. your child should know that ignorance in this area is not an excuse for their behavior and once they have violated another person, they have caused trauma and depending on the nature of the violation, a simple "i'm sorry or i didn't know" can't fix the damage they have inflicted. make sure your child knows......have the conversations!!! #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #sexcrimes #rapevictims #rape #victims #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate

text:
shame, guilt, fear, possible ridicule, not being believed, the list goes on. this is #whyididntreport the traumas i have been through. rape culture and victim blaming is still so prevalent. how many more hashtag movements do we need till everyone realises that harassment, assault and rape are the perpetrators fault and not the victims? ‚ûñ

it doesn't matter if it happened 20years ago, 2 months ago or even 2 days ago. let's make it possible and give the right support to let others not feel shame and guilt and be able to open up. i believe you all. i support you. ‚ù§

text:
heavy, angry and yet hopeful. .
how i‚Äôm feeling about all the things. it‚Äôs easy to focus on the evil, especially when you‚Äôre fighting to change it. but in the darkness i still see light- in the kindness of others showing up, in the bravery of those speaking out, and even in these squares. .
in my experience, growth and change hurt. but the pain is moving us forward and bringing us together. and that is beautiful.

text:
it‚Äôs always been hard to be a woman. but we are living in a time when it‚Äôs especially hard, to see that all the work we‚Äôve done is under siege, threatening to be undone.
‚Ä¢
when we‚Äôre told we‚Äôre the wrong gender, and too gentle to be in this rough game. we were made for gentle loving and soft talk, homemaking and being pretty as a flower.
‚Ä¢
that we shouldn‚Äôt set our dreams too high, expect too much, not because we don‚Äôt deserve it, but because we learn to compromise early. that we should be careful not to say or read or write the wrong thing, for what will people (read men) think?
‚Ä¢
that when we cry or confront, we‚Äôre being temperamental wrecks, but when a man chokes and shouts, he‚Äôs being righteously offended. when, when a girl speaks out about a breach of the sanctity of her body, she is questioned and cross examined and has somehow lost her honour, but the man who had the audacity to touch what is not his is just being a man.
‚Ä¢
when we raise our sons to be demanding and entitled, but our daughters to be accommodating, so he stands proud under the illusion of his own worth, while she learns to bend in the gusts of society‚Äôs winds.
‚Ä¢
that as women, we can‚Äôt and we shouldn‚Äôt.
‚Ä¢
‚Äúcurse this world for what it does to the mothers, for what it does to the daughters. curse it for making us strong through loss and pain, our hearts torn from our chests again and again. curse it for forcing us to endure.‚Äù ‚Äì @sabaatahir
‚Ä¢
it‚Äôs hard and it‚Äôs a daily struggle.
‚Ä¢
but lately, i‚Äôve gotten to a place where every time someone pushes me down, every time i read the news, my heart picks itself up off the ground and takes strength in the conviction that i am not alone in this fight. i remember my sisters all around the world who are fighting on the frontlines, doing this day in and day out, have managed to push forward and still be who they are.
‚Ä¢
i‚Äôve learnt to take heart in the joy for this very moment - that i am alive, the sun is shining, work is good, and my lord is merciful.
‚Ä¢

check out this girl.
killing it in her dungarees and her duck wellies. ( man i wish i still had these! )
if i met this girl i would give her the biggest cuddle and tell her that no matter what she never needs to change who she is for anything or anyone.

i would tell her that no matter how hard life gets it is all coming to you for a reason. that she is going to be important, to uplift others and she is going to be happy.

text:
these are my favorite ladies, and this is the archway we built for my wedding last month. the funny thing about this project is that it was so much easier than i thought it would be! (it was about 15 feet tall and irregularly shaped.) when i told becca (middle) about that, she said it‚Äôs typical for women to think they‚Äôre going to fail when hey begin a project, whereas men expect to succeed.
-
at the farm and in the flower studio, i am constantly checking my implicit expectation of failure. nowhere is that more true than with tractor projects, which i‚Äôm doing a lot of right now. when a machine is broken or needs adjusting, my go-to mindset is often, ‚Äúoh no! this is never going to work!‚Äù but then i remind myself how far i‚Äôve come, and how i always figure it out, and how i am thinking about it the wrong way, and i move forward. and i figure it out! many times, when i‚Äôm working on a physical project (lifting something or attaching something), i quit too soon because i assume i‚Äôm not strong enough. when i call josh and ask him how he manages to lift x piece of equipment with one hand while turning y piece of equipment, he laughs and explains that it‚Äôs not strength that gets the job done. it‚Äôs smarts. my assumption that i‚Äôm not strong enough sells me short! farming takes perseverance and problem solving.
-
i think becca‚Äôs right: women often see themselves as incapable. part of the inequality women experience is internalized, and it‚Äôs up to us to change the way we see ourselves. flower farming is a woman majority industry, which is fascinating. it‚Äôs so important for flower farmers to examine the ways our culture is holding us back. society teaches women to be suspicious of one another, to compete. we have to focus on mutual support and friendship. culture says we‚Äôre not strong enough ‚Äî but we‚Äôre learning we are. male dominated economics says profit comes through self serving action, but we know that behavior is complex and doing good and making money can go hand in hand.
-
no one likes to see oneself as lesser than. but i think current events show us how unheard and underrepresented women remain. let‚Äôs fix it from within and without!

i was around 10 years old and i spent a lot of time in my grandmas friends homes (she loved playing mahjong!). i specifically remember this one day, my grandmas friends son (he was definitely in his 30s and was a bit ‚Äúoff‚Äù) called me into his room to ‚Äúplay‚Äù with him. i of course a child was thrilled to receive attention and the opportunity to play a game.. i entered his room and he offered me a sunkist soda and then told me to sit on his lap.  which i did because i don‚Äôt know any better as a kid and he continued to reach down into my pants/underwear and touched me inappropriately.  i jumped.  ran into the bathroom and stood in there in awe of what just happened. i was shocked and really confused.  i eventually told my grandparents but they didn‚Äôt understand me.
.
.
.
i never told anyone else besides my therapist and i‚Äôve lived with this feeling deep in my gut every time i think about that day.  it‚Äôll never leave me... that disgust and confusion.  i‚Äôm posting this because as a victim, even at 10 years old.. we never forget.  i‚Äôve forgotten many things surrounding that day like how we got there or how long we stayed but yes president trump i can remember every small detail of the assault because it actually happened to me.
.
